ECH 001Y A12 - Design of Coffee–An Introduction to Chemical Engineering
Registered

Course Notes:
** ECH 001Y COURSE MATERIALS AND SERVICES FEE - $30.00 **
Instructor(s): W. Ristenpart, T. Kuhl
Description:
Non-mathematical introduction to how chemical engineers think, illustrated by elucidation of the process of roasting and brewing coffee. Qualitative overview of the basic principles of engineering analysis and design. Corresponding experiments testing design choices on the sensory qualities of coffee.
Course Credit Limitation: Not open for credit to students who have completed ECH 001, ECM 001, ECM 005 or ECH 005.
GE Courses: SE,SL,VL

Functions, limits, continuity. Slope and derivative. Differentiation of algebraic and transcendental functions. Applications to motion, natural growth, graphing, extrema of a function. Differentials. L'Hopital's rule.

                                                                            Students who wish to graduate in 4 years should strive to enroll in 15 units per quarter.

                                                                            If you are a Cal Grant recipient, per state law - Assembly Bill No. 2248, we are required to inform you:

                                                                            1. A Cal Grant award is limited to four academic years, except as provided in California Education Code subdivision (c) of Section 69433.6.
                                                                            2. A student needs to take 15 units per semester or the equivalent quarter units, or 30 semester units or the equivalent quarter units per academic year in order to graduate within four years.*
                                                                            *At UC Davis, the equivalent quarter units are 15 units per quarter or 45 units per academic year. Students are only required to be enrolled in 12 quarter units for the full Cal Grant amount to disburse each term.
